## Priority 1 — Critical Foundation (do these first)

### 🔴 P1.1 — Migrate ALL user data to `~/Documents/cloud_health/`
**Why first:** Beta5 is half-migrated. Frontend logs go to `~/Documents/cloud_health/log/` but credentials, program directory, version file, and salt all still live in `~/.cloud_health/`. Per design decision 1, the legacy path is being eliminated entirely.
**Status: ✅ DONE** (merged via PR #6, commit c899697 + #5/PR #6 follow-ups) — bootstrapper, credentials, and config now use `~/Documents/cloud_health/`; frontend file logging removed in favour of bastion-side logs.

**Tasks:**
- Define a single `USER_DATA_DIR = Path.home() / "Documents" / "cloud_health"` constant in a shared module (e.g. `bootstrapper/paths.py` or read from a tiny config in both bootstrapper and frontend)
- Move credential cache: `~/.cloud_health/.creds_cache` → `~/Documents/cloud_health/credentials.cache`
- Move salt file: `~/.cloud_health/.salt` → `~/Documents/cloud_health/.salt`
- Move version file: `~/.cloud_health/version.txt` → `~/Documents/cloud_health/version.txt`
- Move program directory: `~/.cloud_health/program/` → `~/Documents/cloud_health/program/`
- Move `.meta` file: `~/.cloud_health/.meta` → `~/Documents/cloud_health/.meta`
- Update `frontend/core/credentials.py`: `CACHE_DIR = Path.home() / "Documents" / "cloud_health"`
- Update `bootstrapper/bootstrapper.py`: all `CACHE_DIR`-derived paths
- **No fallback to `~/.cloud_health/`** — per design decision 1, hard cutover
- Add a single startup check that creates `~/Documents/cloud_health/` and required subdirs (`log/`, `db/`, `program/`, `outputs/`) if missing
- Update README to document the new location and note that existing beta5 users must re-enter credentials once

**Files affected:** `bootstrapper/bootstrapper.py`, `frontend/core/credentials.py`, `frontend/core/config.py`, `frontend/app.py`, `README.md`

---

### 🔴 P1.2 — No-install Windows bootstrapper executable
**Why first:** Currently the bootstrapper assumes Python is installed on the user's Windows machine. Most ops users don't have admin rights and can't install Python. This is the #1 first-time-user failure mode.
**Status: NOT STARTED**

**Tasks:**
- Create PyInstaller build spec: `--onefile --noconsole --name CloudHealth-Bootstrap.exe`
- Bundle Python runtime + paramiko + cryptography + http.server inside the exe
- Add a small `.bat` wrapper for users who want to see console output during troubleshooting
- Test on locked-down Windows 10/11 (no admin, AppLocker, Windows Defender SmartScreen)
- **No code signing** per design decision 2 — accept SmartScreen warning
- Document in README the SmartScreen workflow: "Click More info → Run anyway" with screenshot
- Add build script to repo: `bootstrapper/build.bat` (Windows) and `bootstrapper/build.sh` (Linux/Mac for cross-build via wine if needed)
- Verify the exe runs correctly on a clean Windows machine with no Python installed

**Files affected:** new `bootstrapper/build.spec`, new `bootstrapper/build.bat`, new `bootstrapper/build.sh`, repo `README.md`

---

### 🔴 P1.3 — Pre-flight credential validation before SFTP push
**Why first:** Carry-over from earlier review (still PENDING per beta5 issues file). Currently if SSH auth fails on a cluster bastion, the user only sees a generic exception. Must validate connectivity + auth + Python availability across all selected clusters before starting the actual run.
**Status: ✅ DONE** (merged via PR #6, commit 7492291) — `frontend/core/preflight.py` added with parallel checks, "Run Pre-flight Only" button and override checkbox in UI.

**Tasks:**
- New module `frontend/core/preflight.py`
- For each selected cluster: try SSH connect → run `python3 --version` → check `/opt/cloud_health/version.txt` accessible
- Aggregate results into a table: `cluster | reachable | auth OK | python ready | backend version | status`
- Display table in browser before allowing Run to proceed
- **Default behaviour blocks the run on any cluster failure** per design decision 5
- Provide checkbox: "Ignore failures and proceed anyway" (default unchecked)
- Optional "Skip pre-flight" checkbox for power users (default: pre-flight enabled)
- On version change (newly pushed backend), do deeper pre-flight: actually start the backend on each bastion and ping it before declaring ready
- Pre-flight runs in parallel respecting `parallel_limit`
- Pre-flight result table also written to history DB (when P3.1 lands) for audit

**Files affected:** new `frontend/core/preflight.py`, `frontend/app.py` (add WebSocket action `preflight`), `frontend/static/index.html` (preflight UI with override checkbox)

---

## Priority 2 — Core User Control & Reliability

### 🟠 P2.1 — Cancel / Stop button (with partial results saved)
**Why high:** Once a run starts, the user has no way to abort cleanly. Closing the browser orphans backends until the heartbeat watchdog kicks in. Blocks confident production use.
**Status: ✅ DONE** (merged via PR #6, commit d861034) — Stop button + `cancel` WebSocket action; backend snapshots partial results with `status='CANCELLED'` to `~/Documents/cloud_health/last_run_cancelled.json` until P3.1 lands.

**Tasks:**
- Add "Stop" button to `frontend/static/index.html`, visible only when run is active
- New WebSocket action `cancel` from UI → frontend
- Frontend cancels `_RUN_TASK` on each cluster, sends `cancel` action over the SSH-tunneled WebSocket to each bastion backend
- Backend cancels its `_RUN_TASK`, releases lock; in-flight SSH sessions from the bastion to cluster nodes are torn down naturally as coroutines unwind — no explicit kill step needed
- **Partial results saved to history DB with `status='CANCELLED'`** per design decision 4 (when P3.1 lands; until then, save to `results.json` with cancelled marker)
- Frontend tunnel manager closes all tunnels on cancel
- Test partial-state cleanup: cancel during SFTP push, during check execution, during cleanup
- UI shows "Cancelling…" → "Cancelled" state clearly
- Cancelled runs visible in history view (P3.2) with a distinct icon

**Files affected:** `frontend/static/index.html`, `frontend/app.py`, `frontend/core/ws_proxy.py`, `backend/main.py`, `backend/check_runner.py`

---

### 🟠 P2.2 — Bug carry-overs from earlier review
**Why high:** These are real defects that affect production stability. Renumbered from P2.3 in v1 because we want them addressed alongside Cancel.
**Status: ✅ DONE** (merged via PR #6, commit d861034)

**Tasks:**
- ✅ **Frontend lock-state query:** SSH-side probe of `/tmp/cloud_health/hc.lock` between connect and SFTP push, with PID liveness check; raises "Another run in progress (PID X, started Y by Z)" on conflict. Stale locks are ignored — backend cleans them up itself.
- ✅ **Host checks command logging:** `backend/checks/host_checks.py` already routes every `ssh.run()` call through `_r()` → `sec.append_log()`, matching the `ocp_checks.py` and `cvim_checks.py` pattern.
- ✅ **Backend log readback on launch failure:** On `_wait_for_port` timeout, last 50 lines of `/tmp/cloud_health/backend.log` are read over SSH (before pkill, so stderr isn't lost) and appended to the surfaced `TimeoutError`.

**Files affected:** `backend/main.py`, `backend/checks/host_checks.py`, `frontend/app.py`

---

## Priority 3 — Highest-Leverage Feature: History & Diff

### 🟠 P3.1 — SQLite run history database
**Why high:** Single most valuable feature in the entire backlog. Unlocks diff reporting, "view last run", trend analysis, scheduled runs, and any future alerting. Cost is small (~200 lines of code), value is huge.
**Status: ✅ DONE** — `frontend/core/history_db.py` with WAL SQLite, full schema, pruning; wired into `_run_all_clusters`; `/api/history` and `/api/history/{run_id}` endpoints; `history_max_runs: 200` in config

**Tasks:**
- New module `frontend/core/history_db.py`
- Database file: `~/Documents/cloud_health/db/history.db`
- Schema:
  - `runs(id PK, run_id, user, started_at, finished_at, cluster_count, status, source ENUM[ui,cli,scheduled,dry_run])`
  - `cluster_results(run_id FK, cluster_name, cluster_type, pass_count, fail_count, warn_count, duration_s, status, login_success)`
  - `check_results(run_id FK, cluster_name, section_name, message_index, status, message, detail, command)` — natural key: `(run_id, cluster_name, section_name, message_index)`
- Write on every completed run (including cancelled) in a single transaction
- **Pruning policy:** retain last `history_max_runs` runs per design decision 3
- Add `history_max_runs: 200` to `config.yaml` with comment explaining the variable
- Read `history_max_runs` from config; on each new run completion, prune oldest beyond the limit
- Add `/api/history?limit=30` and `/api/history/{run_id}` endpoints
- Indexes: `runs(started_at DESC)`, `cluster_results(run_id, cluster_name)`, `check_results(run_id, cluster_name, status)`

**Files affected:** new `frontend/core/history_db.py`, `frontend/app.py`, `config/config.yaml`, `backend/engine/inventory.py` (add `history_max_runs` to AppSettings)

---

### 🟠 P3.2 — History tab
**Why high:** Direct user request from the original 14 items. Pairs naturally with P3.1.
**Status: ✅ DONE** — "History" tab in sidebar; loads last 30 runs from `/api/history`; click any run shows per-cluster P/F/W summary panel; lazy-loads on first tab activation

**Tasks:**
- Add "History" tab to sidebar showing last 30 runs (timestamp, user, cluster count, P/F/W counts, status icon including CANCELLED)
- Click any historical run → renders the report from saved data without re-running
- "Run only failed clusters" pre-selects clusters from the last run that had `fail_count > 0` (depends on P3.4 per-cluster selection)
- Standalone "View History" entry point — useful when user just wants to check yesterday's results

**Files affected:** `frontend/static/index.html`, `frontend/app.py`, `frontend/core/reporter_html.py`

---

### 🟠 P3.3 — Diff-from-last-run highlighting in report
**Why high:** Direct user request. The "killer demo" feature — turns one-shot diagnostic into operational monitoring.
**Status: ✅ DONE** — `reporter_html.py` accepts `diff_data`; NEW badge (red) on new failures/warnings; RESOLVED badge + strikethrough in collapsible "Resolved" subsection; "What's Changed" banner at top of report; diff built in `_run_all_clusters` via `history_db.get_previous_checks`

**Tasks:**
- On report generation, query DB for previous successful run's results for each cluster (skip cancelled runs as comparison baseline)
- Compute diff per cluster: new failures, resolved failures, new warnings, status flips
- Add "What's Changed" banner at top of report: "3 new failures since [previous run timestamp], 1 resolved, 2 new warnings"
- Highlight new-failure rows with visual indicator (red border + "NEW" badge)
- Highlight resolved rows with strikethrough + "RESOLVED" badge in a separate "Resolved" section

**Files affected:** `frontend/core/reporter_html.py`, `frontend/core/history_db.py`

---

